### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler, core

### Description

We created a shared UI library with lit and are exporting plain web components to be used in any web application. Our library exports a [custom-elements-manifest](https://github.com/webcomponents/custom-elements-manifest) as well as the basic class types on the HTMLElementTagNameMap like this:
```
export default class Switch extends HTMLElement {
  // component logic
}

declare global {
  interface HTMLElementTagNameMap {
    'dss-switch': Switch;
  }
}
```

We have not been able to find a way to tell Angular to use these definitions to have proper typing support in the templates using our custom elements. Is there any plan to support this in the future or did I miss something that already exists?

### Proposed solution

Use types in HTMLElementTagNameMap for basic property binding.
Support custom-element-manifest to increase type support in templates when using custom elements.

### Alternatives considered

JetBrains have come up with "web-types.json" that can provide these type infos but I'd appreciate a solution that is more global.

Adds the necessary compiler changes to support input transform functions. The compiler output has changed in the following ways:

### Directive handler
The directive handler now extracts a reference to the input transform function and it resolves the type of its first parameter. It also asserts that the type can be referenced in the compiled output and that it doesn't clash with any pre-existing `ngAcceptInputType_` members.

### .d.ts
In the generated declaration files the compiler now inserts an `ngAcceptInputType_` member for each input with a `transform` function. The member's type corresponds to the type of the first parameter of the function, e.g.

```typescript
// foo.directive.ts
@Directive()
export class Foo {
  @Input({transform: (incomingValue: string) => parseInt(incomingValue)}) value: number;
}

// foo.directive.d.ts
export class Foo {
  value: number;
  static ngAcceptInputType_value: string;
}
```

### Type check block
If an input has `transform` function, the TCB will use the type of its first parameter for the setter type. This uses the same infrastructure as the `ngAcceptInputType_` members.

### Directive declaration
The generated runtime directive declaration call now includes the `transform` function in the `inputs` map, if the input is being transformed. The function will be picked up by the runtime in the next commit to do the actual transformation.

```typescript
// foo.directive.ts
@Directive()
export class Foo {
  @Input({transform: (incomingValue: string) => parseInt(incomingValue)}) value: number;
}

// foo.directive.js
export class Foo {
  ɵdir = ɵɵdefineDirective({
    inputs: {
      value: ['value', 'value', incomingValue => parseInt(incomingValue)]
    }
  });
}
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

common

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

If you create a Project in angular 16 with
```bash
ng new angular-16-clean --routing --style=scss --prefix=app --standalone
```
Then add @angular/localize:
```bash
ng add @angular/localize
```
and then add cypress for e2e testing
```
ng add @cypress/schematic
```
A problem occurs where the configured Schematics in the `angular.json` (here an example):
```json
{
  "$schema": "./node_modules/@angular/cli/lib/config/schema.json",
  "version": 1,
  "newProjectRoot": "projects",
  "projects": {
    "angular-16-clean": {
      "projectType": "application",
      "schematics": {
        "@schematics/angular:component": {
          "style": "scss",
          "changeDetection": "OnPush",
          "viewEncapsulation": "None",
          "skipTests": false,
          "standalone": true,
          "prefix": "app"
        },
        "@schematics/angular:directive": {
          "prefix": "app",
          "standalone": true
        },
        "@schematics/angular:guard": {
          "functional": true,
          "implements": [
            "CanActivate"
          ]
        },
        "@schematics/angular:interceptor": {
          "functional": true
        },
        "@schematics/angular:library": {
          "prefix": "wl",
          "standalone": true
        },
        "@schematics/angular:pipe": {
          "standalone": true
        },
        "@schematics/angular:resolver": {
          "functional": true
        },
        "@schematics/angular:web-worker": {
          "snippet": true
        }
      },
      "root": "",
      "sourceRoot": "src",
      "prefix": "app",
      "architect": {
      }
    }
  }
}
```
If i now try to generate a component (or a other angular schematic) I encounter, that it doesn't apply the schematic to the command - it tries to use the default schematic - noticeable with compoennt, because they now throw an error because they don't find a module to get imported in:

```bash
% ng g c home
Could not find an NgModule. Use the '--skip-import' option to skip importing in NgModule.
```

I debbuged it and when i delete the following part in the angular.json it is working again:
```json
{
  "cli": {
    "schematicCollections": [
      "@cypress/schematic",
      "@schematics/angular"
    ]
  }
}
```
and I think it must be the `"@cypress/schematic"` part.

